04240nam a22006855i 9781400827954DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20072007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008279547 a10.1515/97814008279542doi  a(DE-B1597)446563  a(OCoLC)979592687  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPOL0400302bisacsh  aMC 6390qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122402:1 aBrenkman, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cultural Contradictions of Democracy :bPolitical Thought since September 11 /cJohn Brenkman.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Political Thought in The Fog of War -- tSeized by Power -- tThe Imagination of Power -- tSeptember 11 and Fables of the Left -- tIraq: Delirium of War, Delusions of Peace -- tThe Ordeal of Universalism -- tConclusion: Prelude to the Unknown -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince 9/11, American foreign policy has been guided by grand ideas like tyranny, democracy, and freedom. And yet the course of events has played havoc with the cherished assumptions of hawks and doves alike. The geo-civil war afflicting the Muslim world from Lebanon through Iraq and Afghanistan to Pakistan confronts the West with the need to articulate anew what its political ideas and ideals actually are. In The Cultural Contradictions of Democracy, John Brenkman dissects the rhetoric that has corrupted today's political discourse and abused the idea of freedom and democracy in foreign affairs. Looking back to the original assumptions and contradictions that animate democratic thought, he attempts to resuscitate the language of liberty and give political debate a fresh basis amid the present global turmoil. The Cultural Contradictions of Democracy picks apart the intellectual design and messianic ambitions of the neoconservative American foreign policy articulated by figures such as Robert Kagan and Paul Berman; it casts the same critical eye on a wide range of liberal and leftist thinkers, including Noam Chomsky and Jürgen Habermas, and probes the severe crisis that afflicts progressive political thought. Brenkman draws on the contrary visions of Hobbes, Kant, Max Weber, Hannah Arendt, and Isaiah Berlin in order to disclose the new contours of conflict in the age of geo-civil war, and to illuminate the challenges and risks of contemporary democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracy. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Judicial Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082795440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400827954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400827954.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK